**ExpandableText** detects when its content is truncated and shows an expand/collapse button — the button stays hidden while the content fits. It has two independent axes you choose between:

- **Truncation direction** — `horizontal` (one line) or `vertical` (a fixed number of lines)
- **Expansion mode** — `inline` (reveal in place) or `dialog` (open a dialog with the full text)

<%= embed OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponentPreview, :default %>

For more variations, browse the [preview examples](/lookbook/inspect/OpenProject/Primer/expandable_text_component/default) in Lookbook.

## Choosing a direction

| Direction | What you get | Reach for it when |
|-----------|--------------|-------------------|
| `horizontal` (default) | A single line, cut off with an ellipsis (`…`) | Short labels in table cells or list rows — permission names, statuses |
| `vertical` | The first `lines:` rows, then clamped | Multi-line descriptions or rich-text previews |

`vertical` takes a `lines:` count (1–6, default 3):

<%= embed OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponentPreview, :vertical %>

## Choosing an expansion mode

| Mode | Behaviour | Reach for it when |
|------|-----------|-------------------|
| `inline` (default) | Clicking the expander toggles the full text in place | Short content that reads fine expanded inline |
| `dialog` | The expander opens a dialog showing the full content | Long-form or formatted content better shown in a focused dialog |

In `dialog` mode the component owns the dialog and wires the expander button to
it. By default — with no `dialog` slot — it renders a dialog showing the full
content, which is all most callers need:

```erb
<%%= render(OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponent.new(direction: :vertical, lines: 2, expansion: :dialog)) do %>
  <%%= full_text %>
<%% end %>
```

<%= embed OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponentPreview, :dialog %>

Supply a `dialog` slot only when you need a custom title, header or body:

```erb
<%%= render(OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponent.new(direction: :vertical, lines: 2, expansion: :dialog)) do |component| %>
  <%% component.with_dialog(title: "Full description", size: :large) do |dialog| %>
    <%% dialog.with_header(variant: :large) %>
    <%% dialog.with_body_content(full_text) %>
  <%% end %>
  <%%= truncated_preview %>
<%% end %>
```

The two axes are independent. In practice two combinations cover almost every
case: **horizontal + inline** (table and list labels) and **vertical + dialog**
(long project attributes). The other combinations are valid too.

## Used in

- **Administration > Users and permissions > Permissions report** — horizontal inline (permission names in table cells)
- **Administration > Work packages > Edit workflow** — horizontal inline (status names)
- **Project attributes** — vertical dialog (via `AttributeComponent`, which composes `ExpandableTextComponent`)

<%= embed OpPrimer::ExpandableTextComponentPreview, :in_table %>

## Best practices

**Do**

- Always place the component inside a width-constrained parent so truncation can trigger
- Pass `flex: 1` when using inside a flex container to allow the truncation wrapper to shrink
- Use the component even for text that might not truncate — the expander stays hidden when content fits

**Don't**

- Don't set a fixed width on the component itself — constrain the parent container
- Don't use horizontal mode for multi-line content — use `direction: :vertical` with a `lines:` count

## Technical notes

The component is a flex container with two children:

- **Truncation wrapper** — `Primer::Beta::Truncate` for horizontal (single-line `text-overflow: ellipsis`) or `OpPrimer::VerticalTruncateComponent` for vertical (multi-line `-webkit-line-clamp` via `.op-vertical-truncate--lines-N`)
- **Expander button** — a `Primer::Alpha::HiddenTextExpander`, initially hidden, shown by the private `expandable-text` Stimulus controller when overflow is detected

The private `expandable-text` Stimulus controller (for `ExpandableTextComponent` only):

- Uses `ResizeObserver` (via `stimulus-use`) to reactively detect when content overflows its container
- **Horizontal:** compares `scrollWidth > clientWidth` on the `.Truncate-text` element
- **Vertical:** compares `scrollHeight > clientHeight` on the truncation target (works with `-webkit-line-clamp`)
- Toggles `Truncate--expanded` (horizontal) or `op-vertical-truncate--expanded` (vertical) for inline expansion
- Updates `aria-label` and `aria-expanded` for accessibility
